{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633070"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17459"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70880"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70880"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECities typically experience higher temperatures compared to surrounding rural areas. This phenomenon affects human health and the environment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary cause of the urban heat island effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absorption and retention of heat by dark surfaces","Reduced wind speed","Industrial air pollution","Higher population density","Increased carbon dioxide emissions"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe urban heat island effect is primarily caused by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsorption and retention of heat by dark surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E such as asphalt roads, dark roofs, and concrete buildings. These materials absorb solar radiation during the day and release it slowly at night, leading to consistently elevated temperatures in urban areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced wind speed\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to building configuration but is a contributing rather than primary factor in urban heat islands.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndustrial air pollution\u003C/strong\u003E can trap heat in the urban atmosphere but is not the main mechanism driving the temperature difference.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher population density\u003C/strong\u003E contributes indirectly through increased energy usage and human activity but is not the direct cause.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased carbon dioxide emissions\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to global climate change but do not directly cause localised urban temperature differences.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urban heat island effect is compounded by reduced vegetation, waste heat from buildings and vehicles, and changes in air flow patterns due to urban structures. These factors combine to create significantly warmer microclimates in cities compared to surrounding rural areas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Urban heat islands occur when cities are significantly warmer than surrounding rural areas due to human activities and infrastructure.","The main contributors to urban heat islands are dark surfaces, reduced vegetation, waste heat from buildings/vehicles, and altered air flow patterns.","Urban heat islands can increase energy consumption, air pollution, and heat-related illness in city populations."],"references":["Mohajerani A, Bakaric J, Jeffrey-Bailey T. The urban heat island effect, its causes, and mitigation, with reference to the thermal properties of asphalt concrete. J Environ Manage. 2017;197:522-538. doi:10.1016/j.jenvman.2017.03.095","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:56:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10149"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70880"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun